    <segment id="1" parent="22" relname="span">Intuitiveness is about physical response.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="15" relname="span">  Take for example the 
keyboard which was designed for right handed users.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration">  All of the 
additional features of the keyboard (the number keypad and the 
insert/delete keys, etc) are located on the right side of the 
keyboard.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="10" relname="concession">  Over the years I&apos;ve become familiar with the key pad and 
insert/delete keys,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="16" relname="span"> but the use of them took me years to master </segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="nonvolitional-cause">
because of the locaction and the lack of flexibility with my right 
hand.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="2" relname="elaboration">  They have yet to come out with a left handed keyboard 
designed with these functions on the opposite side.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="17" relname="conjunction">  I&apos;ve noticed 
right handed users are able to quickly learn the keystrokes</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="17" relname="conjunction"> and are 
able to touch type on the number pad.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="13" relname="antithesis">  

Physical response and intuitiveness is something they attempted 
with the keyboard,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="21" relname="span"> but they missed the mark with at least a few 
users.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="20" relname="span">  Unfortunately I don&apos;t think now it would matter.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="19" relname="span">  The 
keyboard is standardized,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> and even left handed users have learned 
to adapt physically.</segment>
